	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				This is a perfect example of something that happens in a group with no organisation. I've fought in groups before where me and a couple of others go off and risk our lives tanking some nasty monsters while the casters and healers naturally hang back. Most times this works great but when you manage to group with the annoying loot picker casters (or worse, tanks) who loot &lt;b&gt;all&lt;/b&gt; your kills while you're still tanking it gets very frustrating and highly unenjoyable.<BR>
<BR>
So really all I'm saying is define a looting policy when you enter a group. Something simple like, rotate good loots through your group (don't allow them to be claimable by any one person) - use your common sense to differentiate between what is and isn't a good loot. Make sure you also split your money!<BR>
<BR>
If you enter a group that doesn't define a loot strategy then really, every soul for themselves.<BR>
<BR>
It's a bit difficult in this case because a very low level character is effectively 'tagging along' with the higher levels. But it's their own fault for not adopting some form of strategy.<BR>
<BR>
I really do think that guide intervention was un-called for. While I do not believe Knibkin was role-playing (his devious side -- something we all have -- just happened to fall in synch with his chosen character), guides should be concentrating on more important issues. It was a group mistake and the group should learn the hard way, rather than learn that every time they make a mistake they can call on a guide to clear the mess up for them.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
